name: hexanedioic acid, monomethyl ester
Reason: The basic unit to consider is hexanoic acid, which has a melting point of around -3.4°C. The introduction of a carboxylic acid group generally raises the melting point due to the capability of forming hydrogen bonds. A carboxylic acid group can contribute roughly +40 to +50°C to the melting point compared to hydrocarbons of similar molecular weight. On the other hand, conversion of one carboxylic acid group into an ester typically lowers the melting point because esters cannot form as strong intermolecular hydrogen bonds as carboxylic acids. The ester group can be expected to reduce the melting point by approximately -20 to -30°C compared to the carboxylic acid. Therefore, considering that one carboxylic acid group remains which would raise the melting point and one is converted to an ester (which would lower the melting point), the effects can partially offset each other. However, since the carboxylic acid's capacity to hydrogen bond is greater than the ester's, the net effect would be an increase but not as much as two carboxylic acids would have contributed.
